  "prompt": "Why is 2000 rupee note introduced and the 1000 rupee note is scraped? Why can't 1000 note also be changed to new ones like the 500?",
  "response": "The introduction of the 2000 rupee note and the withdrawal of the 1000 rupee note by the Indian government in November 2016 were part of a broader effort to combat black money, counterfeit currency, and corruption. Here are some key points regarding this decision:\n\n1. **Counterfeit Currency**: The 1000 rupee note was one of the most circulated high-denomination notes, making it a target for counterfeiters. By scrapping it, the government aimed to curb the circulation of fake currency.\n\n2. **Black Money**: The move aimed to limit the use of high-denomination currency notes in the informal economy, where black money often circulates. The demonetization of the 1000 rupee note was expected to force individuals holding unaccounted wealth to declare it.\n\n3. **Transition to a Higher Denomination**: The introduction of the 2000 rupee note allowed for a smoother transition as it helped in managing cash supply after the withdrawal of the 1000 rupee note. The 2000 note served as legal tender to quickly absorb the vacuum created in the economy due to demonetization.\n\n4. **New Designs and Security Features**: The 2000 rupee note came with advanced security features to prevent counterfeiting, a necessary upgrade that could not be applied to the old 1000 rupee notes.\n\nAs for why the 1000 rupee note was not simply replaced with new versions like the 500 rupee note, here are the reasons:\n\n1. **Complete Withdrawal**: The government aimed for a complete withdrawal of the 1000 rupee note rather than just replacing it, to take significant steps against black money and corruption.\n\n2. **Focus on Lower Denominations**: The focus on introducing the 2000 note as a replacement served to realign the currency structure and address the immediate need for liquidity in the economy.\n\n3. **Streamlining Currency in Circulation**: The decision also aimed to simplify the currency structure over time, promoting greater use of digital transactions and reducing reliance on cash.\n\nIn summary, the introduction of the 2000 rupee note and the scrapping of the 1000 rupee note were strategic moves by the Indian government to tackle economic issues at the time.",
